VL  - 54
IS  - 2
SP  - 429
EP  - 448
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/08/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1996(00)00099-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199600000994
KW  - Multinational corporations
KW  - International trade
KW  - International investment
KW  - Foreign direct investment
AB  - Global patterns of FDI and trade are remarkably similar, yet mainstay theory has them as substitutes. We posit a model where multiproduct, final-goods firms simultaneously engage in intraindustry FDI and intraindustry trade. The logic behind this two-way FDI is analogous to that of two-way trade in the Brander–Krugman reciprocal-dumping model. Namely, multiproduct firms use trade costs to reduce inter-variety competition by placing production of some varieties abroad. Since the varieties are differentiated, all varieties are sold in all markets. Thus while FDI displaces some exports, it also creates trade via reverse imports. This naturally leads to parallelism in the trade and FDI patterns.
